< Review>
The Bitter End is a neighborhood fixture that has been around for a long time. Lots of USF students drink here. The crowd is friendly and usually pretty talkative. It fills up quickly on weekends. They tend to play good music, an eclectic mix of old and new songs. Drinks are strong and reasonably priced. Definitely a local favorite watering hole.</Review>

<Review>Atmosphere is great, there was plenty of seating even with the crowded Saturday night night. Our friend booked the back room for his birthday, so our large group had more space than we normally would've. In the back room, they had extra chairs hanging on the wall that you could pull down if you needed more seating.

The cocktails are delicious and they have a few that are available during happy hour, which goes till 9 even on Saturdays! Happy hour means $7/cocktails & $5 beer/wine. The prices went up to $12/cocktail & $6-8/beer after happy hour ended.

We got there about 8:30 p.m. and parking on the street was easy just around the corner from the bar.</Review>< pics>

< Text>
This place is one of my favorite's in West LA for happy hour.  They usually have two (not great) beers on tap for $5 - and a list of rotating cocktails for $7.

The syrups and mixers are all made in-house and they have some really creative stuff on their rotating cocktail menu.

The reason they get three stars is because, while the bartenders are very nice, I don't get the feeling they "care"...  and I don't mean they don't care in that they won't listen to your problems like Sam or Woody...  I just mean that I would say about 25% of the time, when I order a beer, they give me the wrong one.</Text>

Amazing cocktail bar. Probably the best I have ever had!</Review>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< date>
1537036662479< /date>
< pictures>
None<//pictures>
<userid>115229147619825068250<//userid></record>
</dataset><record>
< Review>
A nicely sized white tile and silver mirror room and a few small tables surrounds a shapely bar adjacent to a small patio, while a silver water cooler stands like a sentinel by the door. The decor is art deco, with an old LA feel that's bright enough to avoid a noir vibe. The cocktail list is old school, with Manhattan's, Old Fashioned's, and some house cocktails that can compete with the classics. No neon green, no hot pink, and not a blender in sight.

Happy hour is from opening at 5 until 9. Select list is $6, along with a bit of beer and wine. Try the list. It's adventurous and better than almost any other Happy Hour list you'll find. Parking can be tricky, and try not to piss off the locals.</Review>

< name>
John M. Kuchta<//name>
<Time>1408779792727< /Time>< rate>
2</rate>
< Review>
I was very excited about this place from the get-go. Prohibition-era cocktails in a semi-casual setting in walking distance of Bigfoot West sounds like a recipe for success. I went in with two of my friends on a weeknight. Now, I'll say this: we were effing enthusiastic about this place. We thought it was going to be awesome, so we were all smiles walking into the bar. Unfortunately the tall hipster brunette (who could lie in the shade of a barbed wire fence) checking IDs at the front could barely look up from her novel to acknowledge us. She looked at my ID, then rolled her eyes and sighed. As I best recall, I said, almost reassuringly, "I'm excited for this place." "I'm sure you are," she groaned. Uh, whoa. Yes, I read The Perks of Being a Wallflower in high school and at the time, it was fiercely engrossing to my 15-year-old self, but a hostess's job is to be inviting and warm, and it's the paying customers that provide the means for her paycheck. I worked in hospitality for years before moving up, so I can imagine that maybe she was just having a bad day. Still, having a bad day is no excuse to treat your customers like slime.  We got some drinks. They were fine. We walked away disappointed in the service overall.

Fast forward to a few months later, I visit again just because my friend insisted we see the place. Little did I know Queen Bee had decided to up the ante. We slip in right as the bartenders are making last call, sitting down to order one round, avoiding the girl thus far (she was busy doing some sort of janitorial work, which, on second thought, might be her primary responsibility). Then, not unlike a harpy, she intercepts to say,

"We already called last call."
"Right, we're ordering our last drinks."
"No, we already called last call. That means leave."

With a response that rude, I can only imagine a couple of scenarios. Either she graduated from a women's studies program and could only find work at a place owned by her relatives, or her primary purpose is to balance the gender ratio. Either way, she does a disservice to the entire establishment, not to mention the bartenders, because the drinks were decent and the barkeeps (male, that night) were very professional. They smile, at least.

If you can figure out when she's not working there, then it might be worth checking out. But if Her Hipsterian Majesty is manning the door, you're better off hitting up The Wellesbourne on Pico, which has better drinks and bouncers who are more professional.

On the other hand, maybe she was flirting with me, and I'm just a socially awkward penguin. In any case, no thanks. I'll see her next Tuesday.< /Review>

<Rate>4< /Rate><Review>They put the "old" in Oldfields, but in a good way! Yes, it's another old-fashioned cocktail bar, but the ambience is relaxed and friendly, not snooty and hipsterish. They have a sizable but not overwhelming cocktail menu, as well as some craft beers on tap (just a few, as this is mostly a cocktail place). I got one of their seasonal cocktails--The Kentucky Cure (Bourbon, Branca Menta, Creme De Mure, Lemon Juice, Muddled Blackberries & Mint), and my friend got one of their signature drinks, the Blonde Comet(Bourbon, Peach Liqueur, Lemon Juice, Grapefruit Juice, Angostura Bitters). The drinks were interesting, strong, and reasonably priced. It was definitely a nice place to chill out, especially since there was a really cool DJ spinning that night. I forget the guy's name but he put on a nice variety of 60s, 70s and 80s gems. They may have styled themselves after classic 1930s and 40s lounges, but the vibe was all modern LA. Speaking of LA, parking can definitely be a challenge but if you're willing to walk you can usually find a spot down one of the nearby streets. I need to come back and try their happy hour!< /Review><resp>None< /resp>< user_name>
Stephanie Han<//user_name>

< Review>
I have been training here for roughly seven months now and feel qualified to leave a review.

Short version:

I love this place and would recommend anyone (man/woman/child) come give a class a shot. It's clean, there's plenty of parking and everyone is friendly.

Longer Version:

The curriculum here is centered around self-defense concepts which I feel is essential. While some of the moves you learn here certainly do look cool, they are all centered around keeping you safe in the event somebody bigger and stronger than you decides to do you some wrong.

Most importantly, this stuff works. I'm a relatively big and strong guy but the smaller guys in here with more experience can neutralize me quickly. A truly effective art taught by a very knowledgeable family.

If you're looking to spar in a safe environment, all the guys here are respectful of their training partners and the higher belts are not only patient with new trainees but also very helpful.

-Mike< /Review>

<text>TLDR Version:
I can say I've learned more in 1 year here than all my other years of training combined (2 years fully training, 3 years on and off). Surprisingly, they're better than the Official Gracie Academy. If you don't believe me, at least owe it to yourself to get a free trial at both locations.

Long Version:
These guys need a bad review, all these 5 star reviews makes all the reviews seem fake. Though I won't be the one to give it to them.

A long time ago, I saw a sign for a free trial at Caique Jiu Jitsu Academy and the chance to train at the Official Gracie Academy. My knee jerk reaction was to go train at the Gracie Academy because the Gracies must teach Gracie Jiu Jitsu better than some random guy, why bother wasting my time even trying Caique? I trained at Gracie Academy for a year and only a few years later found out my mistake.

I've trained at the Gracie Academy for a year before switching between many schools over a period of 5 years. This place has the best instruction quality I've seen yet. They are very meticulous about all the details, and that's how you get good at Jiu Jitsu. I can say I've learned more in 1 year here than all my other years of training combined (2 years fully training, 3 years on and off).

They are more interested in your development in Jiu Jitsu and less interested in your money. Promotion tests are completely free. In addition, they are honest to a fault. One of the teachers Thomaz is a very bad salesman. I asked to take a private lesson with him before a promotion test. He said he's seen enough to know that I'll pass and to save my money. In addition, he said that he's not doing private lessons for students who want it just for the promotion test, he wants students who actually know the moves to pass the test and not just cram then forget.

Many years ago, I wrote these guys off because they're only famous in the Jiu Jitsu world and not famous in general (Gracies, famous UFC fighters, etc...). DO NOT make my mistake. At least take a free trial. One of my regrets is not starting here from the very beginning.<//text><gmap_id>0x80dd4a60df41c3ab:0xa49364bbb685e5ff<//gmap_id><user>101042841011160880306</user><Resp>None</Resp>< rating>

< text>
I live blocks away from this school.  I literally walked by this place once a day for 3 years and finally went in to check it out.  I am glad I did, I am not glad that I waited so long!  I was instantly taken by the inviting and warm atmosphere, cool people and great facilities.  One thing that has stuck with me since I started is that all the instructors and Master Caique himself knew and remembered my name after my first class!  For some this may not be a huge thing, but at an academy this large, it is really something remarkable.  I really cannot say enough about the art of BJJ for being a great way to stay in shape, and learn incredibly effective self defense.

You don't have to be anyone with a fighting art background or super athletic, when I first started I was 40 lbs heavier and had no idea what I was doing.  After 8 months I competed in my first tournament and took second place!  Moms, Dads, kids, everyone is welcome and is a really great atmosphere and great way to get out of the "gym".

If you have done your research you will know that this place has an incredible lineage.  Grand Master Helio gave Master Caique his black belt in BJJ and Rickson Gracie himself gave Master Caique his Coral Belt.  Not many schools can claim that.< /text>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
When the student is ready, the teacher will appear...I am very grateful to Master Caique and all the instructors at the academy for teaching my kids and myself BJJ.

My kids and myself have been training at Caique's BJJ academy since 2009.
I originally signed my son up because he was scrawny and I was afraid he would get picked on as he got older.  Four years into it, my son has had to use what he learned twice to protect himself.  The best part about it is he has learned not only to protect himself but done in a manner of control without hurting the aggressor which has helped him garner respect and self confidence.

Master Caique and his staff keep a clean and well run academy emphasizing self defense and practical techniques that you can utilize in various situations (self defense or just rolling with other BJJ practitioners).

If you're curious or want to see why this is such a great BJJ academy, come by during their scheduled classes and observe the curriculum and how it is taught (for both adults and kids)!

BTW, if you think you're too old to learn BJJ, think again.  There are students from all walks of life ages 5 up to 60+ at the academy and it is a great environment conducive to learning.</review>

Wesley Yue</user_name>
<Text>tldr: scammers; tried to bill me for work they didn't do. Avoid and don't rely on them being honest if you don't know your stuff. The mechanic that I talked to was Allan.

Came for a smog check. For context, your car computer (ecu) does a bunch of self diagnostics for smog that get reset if it loses power (replacing battery). These self-tests will run again as you drive more miles (called drive cycle). I mentioned that I recently replaced my car battery but also drove a bunch of miles after the replacement so the self-diagnostics should be there. When I came to pick up the car they tried to bill me for $100 in labor on top of the $60 smog check claiming that they had to reset the ECU and do a drive cycle themselves to get the self-diagnostics. I pointed out that the milage on the car did not change while it was in the shop, which is not possible if they actually did a drive cycle. They had a bunch of excuses but eventually wrote off the $100. Also tried to upsell me on a bunch of BS like $110 for an cabin air filter change (a $15 part and a one minute job that anyone can do). The upsell and high prices I can look past, but the dishonesty and fraud for work they didn't do is inexcusable. The extra stupid part was that I had a minor fender bender that I asked for a quote for before they tried to scam me which would've been easily an extra honest $1k that they could've made, but I'm definitely not giving them my business now.

Update Nov 24, 2020 ‚Äì Replying to the owner's reply:
I checked with a different mechanic before writing this review. It is impossible that you reseted the ECU and did a drive cycle while accumulating ZERO miles. When I left I was specifically told that the mechanic that did the work on my vehicle would call to explain why they attempted to charge me for that work, which they never did. I can only imagine why. I was not discounted anything. I was charged $96.50 for the labour that you didn't do, and $58.2 for the smog check, which is the same price as listed on your website. I paid $58.2+tax when I left the shop. Removing $96.50 for work you didn't do is not a discount.< /Text><date>1606256054359<//date>< gmapID>
0x808fa4a671f4cac3:0x49fd2870aa28dba7< /gmapID>

<user>107934205003931989613</user><rate>1<//rate>< Review>
Writing on Yelp and Google Reviews for more exposure (Prices and [multiple] experience[s] detailed below!].  Warning: long review.  TLDR: they are nice, but they are very expensive, they will take advantage of you, and they charge unnecessarily when they can.

I don't believe anyone should be taken advantage of as much as my girlfriend has been.  I will say that their service seems very friendly, but as I've seen from many other reviews, they charge a lot more than they should against the customers who don't know better as you'll see below.

What should've been a quick diagnostic and battery + starter replacement turned into a $95 + $195 + $180 + $90 = $565 fiasco which resulted in a new battery (at least this was fixed), and her car still dead the next morning.  Now, let me breakdown the prices I mentioned above with her experience (on the days before her birthday today, no less).

On Saturday, she was able to get her car into the shop to diagnose a problem with the electrical system, for at this point the battery had died on her and I had to jump her car.  After about 45 minutes, she walked away with a $95 bill for labor and "No problems found here, no need for a new battery," despite her asking for a new battery in the first place.  This is error #1, as any battery diagnostic should be of no charge (as it is at Autozone or O'Reileys!  Life Pro-tip for you there!), and they "nicely convinced" her against the new battery despite the fact that hers was already 4 years old (good practice is to replace every 5 yrs, so she might as well get it replaced and then run a diagnostics on the problem, but no).  They also mentioned some sort of leaking fluid and to come in ASAP again.  OK, no problem with that, so we will move on to yesterday (Monday).

Car has been OK to this point (thankfully), but to keep ahead on maintenance, she came in to have them check the leaking fluid issue and then Uber'd home.  Several hours later and she gets a call, "Hey, your car won't turn on, so we are going to change the battery, is that OK?"  Perfect!  This is what we wanted in the first place, so she says go ahead.  Later, when she Uber'd back to pick up her car, she was presented with two separate bills; $180 for the Interstate battery (I'd say about $20 high, but no problem since this battery isn't available for the regular customer) and $90 for labor (for about a 5 minute job that the average joe schmoe could do or have done for free at, you guessed it, Autozone/Pepboys/O'Reileys!).  This is error #2.  Now, keep in mind they had already charged her $95 for the "inspection fee" and didn't provide a discount or warranty on their original diagnostic, so the entire battery replacement cost a total of $365 when a typical one (AKA one I did at a Union 76 runs closer to $210, or all of $120 to do by hand if you don't care about the Interstate battery).

Now for error #3 (at least this is my personal opinion).  The final charge of $195 was for the leakage diagnostic.  This service included steam cleaning the engine (hopefully done properly, because some shops use a high pressure/temperature washer too close and can actually damage components in the engine compartment area), waiting for things to dry, then driving around for a couple of miles.  Not only is this about an hour procedure, but they failed to identify the issue and charged her regardless and asked her to return after 50-100 miles with no promise of a discount on return.  The error (and flaw, and this is my personal opinion) is that when someone is running a diagnostic/check for something and cannot figure out what is wrong, then there should not be a charge (or at least a discount if it is figured out later, unlike the battery scenario described above).  Imagine you call a plumber for a toilet that won't flush; he/she attempts to fix it by using a plunger for a bit, doesn't fix the problem, then charges you for his labor and tells you he'll come back later to try again and likely charge you the same amount for labor, then 1.5x for the part.< /Review>

< text>
I came in to the area because I needed a phone repair from someone in the area. I had asked a friend which place was cool to dine at for lunch, and he recommended this place to me along with a link to their site. \

Originally, i thought it was like a Mongolian barbecue place because of how the menu was set up. I also thought it was like a Poke Bar place, but it thought, what the hell, i want to explore something i havent seen or tried, so 6 minute drive later, and easy parking - here I am, enjoying this super delicious bowl i've put together before my very eyes.

I had mine with the Buckwheat Noodle base - Delicious. Also had it with the Peanut sauce. ITS DELICIOUS. im coming back to try the Nori sauce next. I was able to sample it as i was there - it was really good, and it deserved a spot in my belly, but i was in a peanut mood this day, so peanut gets it.

Youre able to get the sauces either on the bowl or in the side. As for to-go, you can also ask for another pack of sauce before you leave. Take-out is very easy - just ask for a lid for your bowl, and youre good to go.

Nice chill place. Youre in and then youre out - very quick, simple, and also very yummy. I recommend it!< /text>

<Time>1508451520821<//Time>< user>

< Date>
1513278607561< /Date>
< Review>
I first learned of On + On because it's Torrance location is close to work, and was happy to see they opened another location in Norwalk. It's like Chipotle in that you pick the components of your bowl at the counter. You get to choose one each of a base, protein, and hot veggie (you can also ask for half/half), and then you can pick as many of the rest of the cold toppings as you want. Everything I've tried is extremely flavorful. The bowl itself is huge and it's a great value because you can get easily full. I usually end up with leftovers. Even better, I feel guilt-free afterwards since it's mostly vegetables! The interior is spacious with ample seating. Parking is generally easy as well since it's in a plaza, though lunch hour sometimes is busy.</Review>

<Review>This review isn't based on the food or the price. Some people like Papa John's, some like Dominos, some like Pizza Hut and most don't like any of the major chains.  (I actually prefer the taste Dominos personally)

This review is based on the service. I've ordered from this Papa John's numerous times and they've always brought my order way faster than I expected (20-30 min on campus on a week night, 25-35 at peak times). Pizzas always arrive piping hot and the delivery guys are all really friendly and professional.  When ordering a lot of pizzas for an event, Papa John's has always delivered right on time unlike some of the other pizza places in town.

The one time they messed up my order, they made it right when I complained.< /Review><Rating>5< /Rating></record></dataset><record>

<user_id>117567607906029395339</user_id><user_name>Sean Yuan</user_name><Date>1517882133577<//Date><Rating>5</Rating>< text>
There is still hope for authentic Southern BBQ in Los Angeles. That hope comes in the name of Boogie McGee's. This family-owned Mississippi style BBQ joint blew me away and made me forget I was in Los Angeles, surrounded by embarrassing displays of Buffalo wing serving "Southern Barbecue" restaurants. Everything is hand-made, family recipe prepared, and you can tell from the very first bite of juicy, tender brisket. Great prices, portions, and food make this my new go-to BBQ spot in LA.

-------Food-------
Brisket (5/5) - This is the money, the cornbread and butter of Boogie's. Incredibly tender and juicy, you can tell from the first bite that this cut was hand rubbed, slow smoked for 8+ hours, no corners cut. The crust on the outside is very well done - just spicy enough to penetrate the fat of the meat.

Beef Ribs (5/5) - To give you an idea of how tender these beef ribs were, as I was handing a rib over to my girlfriend, the bone completely slid out and fell apart from the meat. It's rare to find BBQ joints in LA that have beef ribs, and even rarer for them to be done properly. Cooked to perfection, and again the dry rub really added an extra element to the meat.

BBQ Sauce (4/5) - I had both the House Bourbon Classic BBQ Sauce and ‚ÄãVoodoo Spice BBQ Sauce served on the side so I could try them both with the brisket and ribs. Both sauces have strong hints of bourbon to them which made the traditionalist in me frown. Although I wish they offered a more traditional smoky BBQ sauce, the meat is delicious enough on its own that I quickly forgot about my complaint.

Sides (3/5) - The corn bread was phenomenal - perfectly crispy on the outside and very fluffy on the inside. The dirty rice was also well done, and tasted very authentic. The cole slaw was too mind and seemed like it was missing something. With the combos, they also load your tray up with fresh veggies and a daily chosen side which in our case was Rotini noodles with diced vegetables in a vinaigrette sauce.

-------Staff (5/5)-------
Although Boogie McGee's is a walk-up & order joint, every single person I interacted with from the cashier to the cooks were kind, informative, and you could tell they genuinely cared about their craft.

-------Venue (5/5)-------
My girlfriend and I were the only people there at 5:30pm on a Tuesday. This place should be packed, granted it's a cute place tucked away in a Korea Town plaza, so it's probably the last result when searching for BBQ in the area. The quiet atmosphere actually made for an enjoyable dinner. They play country music and serve sweet tea - not much more you can ask for.< /text>

< review>
Seems like lots of people like this place, but I can't really see why.  This review is for half a rack of ribs with corn pudding and rice.

MEAT:  The meat did indeed fall off the bones, but sadly it tasted more like semi soft cardboard with a crust of peppery sweet rub. Maybe I'm one of the few who actually like to taste the juice of the meat rather than just sauce or rub.  The sauce itself, which was on the side, was not to my liking either.  Kinda like a sweet A1 sauce, in my opinion.  Gimme some meat juice!!

The rice was pretty good.

The salad was drenched with vinegarette which made the odd pairing even less appealing.

I DO love that they put lots of other veggies like carrots and green tomatoes, etc.

The corn pudding tasted ok.  It was also cardboardy, which made me check the cardboard it was on, but still edible.

The cornbread gets a dry 2.5/5.  Made me wish that Kenny Rogers chicken place was still around.  They seemed to have fresh, warm, soft corn bread with kernels inside all the time.

All in all, it was ok.  Luckily I work close by otherwise I would've complained about wasting money on parking too.

Maybe I got a bad batch?  It was 8:30pm and although they close at 10, it did seem like the lady who served me really, really wanted to just go home.  They did end up doing their closing routine at 9, so I just packed up and caught my train.  Hopefully this review can steer away only those like me, who like juicy meat, but also maybe give the owners a chance to review their methods.   Like I said, seems like other people love the place.

Happy eatings!

Oh yeah, i dig the country music and motif inside.  Thumbs up.< /review>

<rate>5< /rate><Review>The. Best. Bbq. I've. Ever. Had. As the great movie Friday after next feat ice cube once said, "BBQ so good, make you wanna slap your momma". I came here curious because I love BBQ but I hate driving out lol so I wanted to find a decent place nearby and I honestly didnt expect to be blown away but boy was I wrong. I ordered the brisket and was so surprised to see how I was able to cut it without using my knife much, the house beer goes so well with the food and makes you think about how well someone put this place together. I barely touched the sauce that it came with because I felt I didnt need it. The vegetables go so well with the food as well as the corn bread. I really like the table layout and the paper towel rolls are so cool altogether it gives it a very homey backyard bbq feel. Service on point. <rate>3< /rate><pics>None< /pics><UserId.>111720664309925578813< /UserId.><date>1601021015935</date>< gmapID>
0x80c2970e79b6817f:0xeba8a4b4b5edab79< /gmapID>
< review>
We came mainly for the burgers so this review will basically be all about that. There is no shortage of parking in the back and we came on a Monday, so it might be different than on weekends. The vibes were akin to an Irish pub with some plush seats at the walls.

Our group basically decided to get 2 Bacon Bourbonators and 2 Morrison Filets. All came with fries and one of my friends decided to get truffle fries for a bit extra.

Fries were crisp, and the truffle fries were good. No issues there, and definitely felt good having those.

As for the burgers, I think they were good but not as crazy good as some people make it to believe. The meat was tender and juicy, but I didn't feel that it justifies the price personally. Still, it was a good burger with few issues.

The drinks were fine. There's a huge selection of drinks that I can appreciate and the all IPAs that I had here were good.

Overall, a good spot for friends and even some family as long as it's a weekday, and while the burger is good I dunno if it's justified for the price.<//review>

< text>
Even before the pandemic, this place would not get the order correct about 50% of the time. My last visit took 2 trips through the drive through, I couldn't go inside to correct the order as they had locked the door due to guidelines, to get a correct order. There was no chance of a misunderstanding as I always ask them to repeat the order back, which he did. What I received however was 2 completely different meals with toppings I specifically asked to be removed. Second time around I received only 1 meal not the second.

This is a fairly busy McDonald's but that's no excuse for quality control. The other McDonalds in the area I've never received an incorrect order from. I won't be coming back to this one as I also get soggy greasy fries about 50% of the time on top of my order being wrong. Too much of a headache to deal with.< /text>

<user_id>118319327888188875437</user_id><username>Del Tafoya</username>< time>
1567531513311< /time>
< rating>
5<//rating>
< Review>
I visited this location between 3-4am on my way home from work. Let's start off with the fact that the grill was being cleaned so they weren't serving burgers for the next 30 minutes or so. Normally this would affect my opinion in a negative manner but the way they handled the situation definitely deserves 5 stars.
I was only able to order chicken nuggets and fries but had originally come to pick up burgers. I'm not sure why but the drive thru line was taking forever so by the time I got to the window to pick up my food, it had been almost 20 minutes. I had asked the woman at the second window if the grill was back on yet since the guy that took my order said if I wanted burgers I'd have to wait 15-20 minutes. She apologized for the misinformation and informed me that it can actually take a little over 30 minutes. Making a long story shorter... This trip took me about 35 minutes but they did compensate me for the inconvenience and handled the situation in a friendly/professional manner.
This is also the only location, closest to Sherman Oaks, that is open 24-7.</Review>
